}




ðŸ§  What is Inheritance?
Inheritance means:
ðŸ”„ "Ek class (child) dusri class (parent) ke properties and methods ko inherit kar sakti hai".

In short:
ðŸ”¸ Code reuse
ðŸ”¸ Hierarchy (parent-child relationship)
ðŸ”¸ Follows "is-a" relationship

âœ… Syntax: extends Keyword
java
Copy
Edit
class Parent {
    // fields and methods
}

class Child extends Parent {
    // inherits everything from Parent
}
ðŸ“Œ extends ka matlab hota hai:
"Ye class us parent class ke saare methods aur variables inherit karegi."

ðŸ§¾ Example: Basic Inheritance
java
Copy
Edit
// Parent class
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("This animal eats food.");
    }
}

// Child class
class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks.");
    }
}
java
Copy
Edit
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d = new Dog();
        d.eat();   // Inherited from Animal
        d.bark();  // Defined in Dog
    }
}




âœ… Types of Inheritance in Java
Java supports Single, Multilevel, and Hierarchical Inheritance
âŒ Java does not support Multiple Inheritance with classes (to avoid ambiguity), but you can achieve it with interfaces.

ðŸ”¸ 1. Single Inheritance
java
Copy
Edit
class A {
    void showA() { System.out.println("Class A"); }
}

class B extends A {
    void showB() { System.out.println("Class B"); }
}
ðŸ”¸ 2. Multilevel Inheritance
java
Copy
Edit
class A {
    void a() { System.out.println("A"); }
}

class B extends A {
    void b() { System.out.println("B"); }
}

class C extends B {
    void c() { System.out.println("C"); }
}
java
Copy
Edit
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        C obj = new C();
        obj.a();  // from A
        obj.b();  // from B
        obj.c();  // from C
    }
}
ðŸ”¸ 3. Hierarchical Inheritance
java
Copy
Edit
class Animal {
    void eat() { System.out.println("eating..."); }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() { System.out.println("barking..."); }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    void meow() { System.out.println("meowing..."); }
}
âŒ Why Java Doesnâ€™t Support Multiple Inheritance with Classes
java
Copy
Edit
class A {
    void show() { System.out.println("A"); }
}

class B {
    void show() { System.out.println("B"); }
}

// class C extends A, B âŒ Not allowed â€“ ambiguity
âœ”ï¸ Java solves this using interfaces, not classes.

ðŸ‘¨â€ðŸ« Why Java Doesnâ€™t Support Multiple Inheritance (with classes)
ðŸ”´ Because it causes confusion called the "Diamond Problem"
ðŸŸ¡ Letâ€™s Break It Down:
âœ… First: What is Multiple Inheritance?
When a class inherits from more than one class, itâ€™s called multiple inheritance.

ðŸ”§ Example in C++ (which allows multiple inheritance):
cpp
Copy
Edit
class A {
    void show();
};

class B {
    void show();
};

class C : public A, public B {
    // Inherits from both A and B
};
â“Problem: What if both A and B have the same method?
cpp
Copy
Edit
class A {
    void show() { cout << "A"; }
};

class B {
    void show() { cout << "B"; }
};

class C : public A, public B {
    // Which 'show()' will C use? A or B?
};
This creates ambiguity/confusion. This is called the diamond problem.


ðŸ§  What is Inheritance?
Inheritance means:
ðŸ”„ "Ek class (child) dusri class (parent) ke properties and methods ko inherit kar sakti hai".

ðŸ§¾ Example: Basic Inheritance
java
Copy
Edit
// Parent class
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("This animal eats food.");
    }
}

// Child class
class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks.");
    }
}
java
Copy
Edit
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d = new Dog();
        d.eat();   // Inherited from Animal
        d.bark();  // Defined in Dog
    }
}



ðŸ”„ What is Method Overriding?
Method Overriding means:
ðŸ” "Child class apne parent class ke method ko dubara define karta hai (same name, same parameters)"

âœ… Overriding allows custom behavior in the child class.

ðŸ“Œ When Do We Use It?
Jab child class parent ka method inherit karta hai

But chahta hai ki apna version implement kare

âœ… Rules of Method Overriding
Method name must be same

Parameters must be same (signature)

Must be inherited from parent class

Cannot override private, static, or final methods

Access modifier should be same or more visible

ðŸ”§ Syntax Example:
java
Copy
Edit
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}
java
Copy
Edit
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal a = new Dog();  // Polymorphism
        a.sound();  // Output: Dog barks
    }
}


 Explanation:
sound() method is defined in parent class Animal

Dog overrides that method to give custom behavior

âœ… We use @Override annotation for clarity (optional, but recommended)



ðŸ”€ Super Keyword with Overriding
Use super.method() to call parent method inside overridden method.

java
Copy
Edit
class Parent {
    void greet() {
        System.out.println("Hello from Parent");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    void greet() {
        super.greet();  // calls parent version
        System.out.println("Hello from Child");
    }
}




âœ… Advanced Example: Polymorphism with Overriding
java
Copy
Edit
class Shape {
    void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing shape");
    }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing circle");
    }
}

class Square extends Shape {
    void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing square");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Shape s;

        s = new Circle();
        s.draw(); // Drawing circle

        s = new Square();
        s.draw(); // Drawing square
    }
}



ðŸ”  What is super keyword?
Java me super ka use child class se parent class ke members (variables, methods, constructor) ko refer karne ke liye hota hai.

ðŸ”¹ Jab child aur parent class me same naam ke methods ya variables hote hain, tab super se parent version ko call kar sakte ho.

âœ… Uses of super keyword:
Use Case	Example
1ï¸âƒ£ Call parent class method	super.methodName()
2ï¸âƒ£ Access parent class variable	super.variableName
3ï¸âƒ£ Call parent constructor	super() (must be 1st line in constructor)



âœ… 1. super.method() â€“ Call parent method
java
Copy
Edit
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void sound() {
        super.sound();  // ðŸ”¹ Call parent method
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d = new Dog();
        d.sound();
    }
}
Output:
Animal makes sound
Dog barks


âœ… 2. super.variable â€“ Access parent variable

class Parent {
    int x = 100;
}

class Child extends Parent {
    int x = 200;

    void show() {
        System.out.println("Child x: " + x);         // 200
        System.out.println("Parent x: " + super.x);  // 100
    }
}
java
Copy
Edit
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Child c = new Child();
        c.show();
    }
}

âœ… 3. super() â€“ Call parent constructor
java
Copy
Edit
class Parent {
    Parent() {
        System.out.println("Parent constructor");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    Child() {
        super(); // ðŸ”¹ Call to parent constructor
        System.out.println("Child constructor");
    }
}
java
Copy
Edit
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Child c = new Child();
    }
}
ðŸ” Output:
kotlin
Copy
Edit
Parent constructor  
Child constructor

âœ… super() always first line in child constructor.
Agar na likho, Java automatically call karta hai super() (default constructor).
